 surname form, <i>de Lauueney</i> (1327) fits better with a different French placename, Lavenay (Sarthe), with vocalization of <i>-v-</i> to <i>-w-</i>."],"variants":[{"name":"Lardner","meanings":["English: metonymic occupational name for a servant in charge of a larder or storeroom for provisions, from Anglo-Norman French, Middle English <i>lardiner</i>, an altered form of Anglo-Norman French <i>larder</i> (from Late Latin <i>lardarium</i>, a derivative of <i>lar(i)dum</i> ‘bacon fat’). Compare   Larder  . According to Reaney, the term <i>lardiner</i> also denoted a servant who oversaw the pannage of hogs in the forest."]},{"name":"Lerner","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Jewish Yakov, Aron, Emanuel, Isadore, Meyer, Hyman, Moisey, Shlomo, Yaacov.","English: variant of   Larner  .","South German: habitational name for someone from Lern near Freising."]}]},{"name":"Michael","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of a common biblical name (meaning ‘who is like God?’ in Hebrew) borne by one of the archangels, the protector of the ancient Hebrews, who is also regarded as a saint of the Catholic Church. In the Middle Ages, Michael was regarded as captain of the heavenly host (see Revelation 12:7–9), symbol of the Church Militant, and patron of soldiers. He was often depicted bearing a flaming sword. The name is also borne by a Persian prince and ally of Belshazzar mentioned in the Book of Daniel. Since the early 1900s it has been one of the most enduringly popular boys' names in the English-speaking world.  See also  Michal ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705201,"age":69,"year":"1549","julianDay":2286821,"title":"Book of Common Prayer","description":"Book of Common Prayer, a product of the English Reformation, was published in 1549 for assistance in the administration of the sacraments and other rites and ceremonies of the church according to the use of the Church of England. The book outlined morning, evening, and communion prayers and orders for baptism and marriage, thus making England a truly Protestant state.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Book_of_Common_Prayer","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Book of Common Prayer","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705202,"age":78,"year":"1558","julianDay":2290108,"title":"Act of Uniformity","description":"The Act of Uniformity was passed by the Parliament of England and required all people to go to church once a week. The consequence of not attending church was a fine of 12 pence, which was a considerable amount for a poor person.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705206,"age":91,"year":"1571","julianDay":2294856,"title":"The Royal Exchange is Organized","description":"The Royal Exchange was organized in January 1571 by Sir Thomas Gresham. Gresham is known as the father of English banking.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705207,"age":105,"year":"1585","julianDay":2299970,"title":"The First English Colony is Established in America","description":"England established its first colony in North America in 1585 as a way to generate additional wealth. The colony was named Virginia, after the virgin Queen Elizabeth I.","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"Michael Larner was born in 1480, in England. He married Sarah in 1504, in England. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter."},"et":{"1480–":"1480–Surnud","1480–Female":"1480–Surnud","1504–1563":"1504–1563","1480–Male":"1480–Surnud","1558":"1558","1585":"1585","1563":"1563","1571":"1571","1480":"1480","1549":"1549","1504":"1504","England":"England","Pimlico St Peter, Middlesex, England":"Pimlico St Peter, Middlesex, England"},"fi":{"1480–":"1480–Kuollut","1480–Female":"1480–Kuollut","1504–1563":"1504–1563","1480–Male":"1480–Kuollut","1558":"1558","1585":"1585","1563":"1563","1571":"1571","1480":"1480","1549":"1549","1504":"1504","England":"England","Pimlico St Peter, Middlesex, England":"Pimlico St Peter, Middlesex, England"},"fr":{"1480–"